## Building a Memory (Flip-card) Game in Angular

**Mental model:** A shuffled deck of paired symbols. Track `flipped` indices (max two) and a `matched` Set. The second flip compares: match keeps them; mismatch flips both back after a delay with input *locked* meanwhile. Classic `NgModule` setup, no `?.`/`??` (the build rejects them).

### Step 1 — Shuffled deck
```typescript
deck = this.makeDeck();
flipped: number[] = [];
matched = new Set<number>();
lock = false;
moves = 0;
```

### Step 2 — Flip with a lock guard
```typescript
flip(i: number): void {
  if (this.lock || this.flipped.indexOf(i) !== -1 || this.matched.has(i)) { return; }
  this.flipped = [...this.flipped, i];
  if (this.flipped.length === 2) { this.resolve(); }
}
```

### Step 3 — Resolve the pair
```typescript
const [a, b] = this.flipped;
this.moves++;
if (this.deck[a].s === this.deck[b].s) { this.matched.add(a); this.matched.add(b); this.flipped = []; }
else { this.lock = true; setTimeout(() => { this.flipped = []; this.lock = false; }, 800); }
```

### Step 4 — Up-state helper + win
```typescript
isUp(i: number): boolean { return this.flipped.indexOf(i) !== -1 || this.matched.has(i); }
get won(): boolean { return this.matched.size === this.deck.length; }
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Triple click | `lock` blocks the third flip. |
| Re-click flipped | `indexOf` guard. |
| Win | `matched.size === deck.length`. |

**Interview tip:** The `lock` during the mismatch `setTimeout` is the crux — without it a quick third click corrupts the pair; mention clearing pending timeouts on reset/destroy in production.

